{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ba3c0796-1130-45af-aa4b-1c565ae62a39","content":"In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events API** on the `MauiAppBuilder` to map platform events to cross-platform hooks.\n\nIn your `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity =>\n        {\n            // Runs on Android OnPause\n        })\n        .OnStop(activity =>\n        {\n            // Runs on Android OnStop\n        }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app =>\n        {\n            // Runs on iOS DidEnterBackground\n        }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` at the top.\n- Platform blocks are guarded with `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives so each compiles only for its target.\n- You can chain multiple events (e.g., `.OnResume(...)`, `.WillEnterForeground(...)`) on the same builder.\n- Other platforms (`Windows`, `MacCatalyst`, `Tizen`) follow the same pattern with `AddWindows(...)`, `AddiOS(...)`, etc.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0e24a2cc-88a3-4f4a-819f-374c747b8788","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development. I can answer this directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":389,"requestId":"A43D:32D1ED:613FEDF:69ACEDE:69F004DF"},"id":"3a92a9ed-810b-4021-ab91-6cefccfa16dc","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:52:56.412Z","parentId":"f12838a4-96b3-423a-a310-65fc7d3eff3d"}
